INSERT INTO historia (catHistoria, idioma, descHistoria) VALUES ('cat1', 'en', 'The name of La Alberca comes from the Hebrew word "bereka", which together with the Arabic article "al", gives rise to "Al-Bereka", meaning "place of waters". Tradition has it that in ancient times, La Alberca was called Valdelaguna because of the abundance of water that surrounds the village, although there are real documents that state that the village was called La Alberca as early as 1215.');
INSERT INTO historia (catHistoria, idioma, descHistoria) VALUES ('cat1', 'en', 'As for the origins of the municipality, the first traces of the history of La Alberca are to be found in prehistoric times, whose traces remain in the cave paintings from the Neolithic period in numerous cliffs and crags in the valleys surrounding La Alberca: the Valle de Lera and Las Batuecas. Even so, many cultures have left their mark on the evolution of the town:');
INSERT INTO historia (catHistoria, idioma, descHistoria) VALUES ('cat1', 'en', 'During the Iron Age, Celtic tribes built a castro on the nearby hill of La Corredera, located at the entrance to the village. After the arrival of the Romans, various villas and farms were built. With the Muslim invasion of the Iberian Peninsula, the area became part of the Caliphate of Córdoba, although there were numerous incursions and conflicts.');
INSERT INTO historia (catHistoria, idioma, descHistoria) VALUES ('cat1', 'en', 'After the Reconquest, La Alberca became part of the Kingdom of León and an important process of repopulation of French origin took place in the area, due in part to D. Raimundo de Borgoña, a French nobleman who married Doña Urraca, one of the daughters of Alfonso VI of León. This fact would explain the large number of French place-names in the southern part of the province of Salamanca.');
INSERT INTO historia (catHistoria, idioma, descHistoria) VALUES ('cat1', 'en', 'In the 13th century, La Alberca was granted the charter of Salamanca, which allowed the town to develop as a commercial and agricultural centre. There is sufficient documentation to prove that La Alberca was a royal manor.');
INSERT INTO historia (catHistoria, idioma, descHistoria) VALUES ('cat1', 'en', 'During the Middle Ages, La Alberca became an important fortified town, and was the scene of numerous battles between the different factions fighting for control of the region. In the 15th century, La Alberca became a town and its period of greatest splendour began, during which numerous monuments and historical buildings were built.');
INSERT INTO historia (catHistoria, idioma, descHistoria) VALUES ('cat2', 'en', 'At the end of the Middle Ages, an event of major importance for the area was the discovery of the image of the Virgen de la Peña de Francia (1434), which turned the sanctuary built thereafter into a place of pilgrimage, which was joined by pilgrims on the Camino de Santiago who followed the so-called "Camino del Sur" along the "Calzada de la Plata". ');
INSERT INTO historia (catHistoria, idioma, descHistoria) VALUES ('cat2', 'en', 'Another important moment in the history of La Alberca, according to tradition, is that in 1465 the women of La Alberca defeated the Portuguese troops of the Prior of Crato; in this victory they snatched from the Portuguese the banner, which is still preserved in the village today. This victory is celebrated on the second day of Easter, Easter Monday.');
INSERT INTO historia (catHistoria, idioma, descHistoria) VALUES ('cat2', 'en', 'At the same time, Juan II made the town of La Alberca dependent on the House of Alba.  He also donated his cloak embroidered with gold thread to the town, from which a chasuble was made, which is the main feature of the Midnight Mass that is held in the town today. Years later, it gained control of part of the Sierra de Francia with the favour of Ferdinand the Catholic, bringing these domains under the jurisdiction of the town of Granadilla in Cáceres.');
INSERT INTO historia (catHistoria, idioma, descHistoria) VALUES ('cat2', 'en', 'Nevertheless, La Alberca managed to maintain a great deal of autonomy with respect to Granadilla, even having its own ordinances in 1515 and Las Hurdes becoming a dehesa of La Alberca until 1835, when what is today the limitation of the provinces of Spain was made, with La Alberca being definitively integrated into the province of Salamanca, within the Region of León. ');
INSERT INTO historia (catHistoria, idioma, descHistoria) VALUES ('cat2', 'en', 'In the 16th century, La Alberca reached its peak of splendour thanks to the wool trade and the cultivation of cereals. As a result, numerous manor houses were built and the infrastructures improved, such as the paving of the streets and the construction of the hermitage of El Humilladero.');
INSERT INTO historia (catHistoria, idioma, descHistoria) VALUES ('cat2', 'en', 'In the Modern Age, La Alberca played an important role in the Spanish War of Independence, during which the inhabitants of the town joined the resistance forces against the French invader. In 1812, French troops invaded La Alberca, sacking and burning several houses and public buildings as they passed, and stealing a large number of valuable objects, such as silverware and paintings, which belonged to the church and the wealthiest families of the village.');
INSERT INTO historia (catHistoria, idioma, descHistoria) VALUES ('cat3', 'en', 'It is said that the mayor of La Alberca led a guerrilla group that opposed the French occupation. He was captured by French troops and condemned to death for treason. However, before he was executed, some say that he managed to escape and flee to the nearby mountains, where he continued to fight against the French. Others tell a different story. It is said that it was the villagers who liberated their mayor from the French.');
INSERT INTO historia (catHistoria, idioma, descHistoria) VALUES ('cat3', 'en', 'During the Spanish Civil War (1936-1939), La Alberca suffered the effects of the conflict, and its inhabitants were affected by the repression and violence of those years. Many residents of La Alberca were forced to abandon their homes and flee to other regions of Spain, France and even Latin America, while others were persecuted and imprisoned for their political ideology.');
INSERT INTO historia (catHistoria, idioma, descHistoria) VALUES ('cat3', 'en', 'After the Civil War, La Alberca began a process of reconstruction and economic recovery, boosted by the development of rural tourism in the area. In 1940, the town became a Historic-Artistic Monument and since then, important restoration and conservation work has been carried out on its heritage. It was the first Spanish municipality to achieve this distinction.');
INSERT INTO historia (catHistoria, idioma, descHistoria) VALUES ('cat3', 'en', 'In the 1960s, La Alberca became one of the main tourist destinations in the Sierra de Francia, thanks to its cultural and natural heritage and its gastronomy. In 1988, La Alberca was twinned with the Murcian village of Alberca de las Torres, so that the two towns were even more united than by name.');
INSERT INTO historia (catHistoria, idioma, descHistoria) VALUES ('cat3', 'en', 'Today, La Alberca is still one of the most visited villages in the Sierra de Francia. In 2014 it was chosen as one of the 7 Rural Wonders of Spain and in 2020 it received the title of "Rural Wonder" in a competition promoted by the Network of the Most Beautiful Villages of Spain. That same year it appeared on the list of the most beautiful medieval villages according to National Geographic and in 2023 it was included in the list of the 20 most beautiful villages in Spain, also according to National Geographic.');
