INSERT INTO monumento (categoriaMon, nombreMon, idioma, descMon) VALUES ('plaza', 'crucero', 'en', 'On the opposite side is the Virgin Mary, on the shaft of the column, the signs of the Passion are sculpted in low relief: the coins of the betrayal of Judas, the whip, the nails and the lance. In addition, in the lower part of the cross, creating a double height in the square, there is a small fountain, very useful for hot days.');
INSERT INTO monumento (categoriaMon, nombreMon, idioma, descMon) VALUES ('plaza', 'crucero', 'en', 'Although today no other image of the square of La Alberca is conceivable without the cross, this has not always been its location. The original location of the cross in the square was the Plaza de San Antonio, at the entrance to the village. Unfortunately, in 1928 a tree fell on it and destroyed it. In 1940, after restoration and despite the refusal of the local residents, it was decided to place it in its current location, and years later it became the main protagonist of the place.');
INSERT INTO monumento (categoriaMon, nombreMon, idioma, descMon) VALUES ('plaza', 'antiguasescuelas', 'en', 'At the top of the square, just in front of the cross, stands a three-storey building with thick colonnaded arcades and curious hexagonal windows at the top. Although restored at the end of the 20th century (1997), this building housed the old schools of La Alberca, before they were established on their present site in 1935.');
INSERT INTO monumento (categoriaMon, nombreMon, idioma, descMon) VALUES ('plaza', 'antiguasescuelas', 'en', 'In earlier times, it is said that on one side of the building, the fraudulent measures of bad tradesmen were displayed. After the relocation of the schools, the building fell into disuse. Years later, it was converted into a dance hall for the enjoyment of the people. Nowadays, the use of the building is completely different from its beginnings: it is home to active catering establishments that are popular with locals and visitors alike.');
INSERT INTO monumento (categoriaMon, nombreMon, idioma, descMon) VALUES ('plaza', 'ayuntamiento', 'en', 'Located on one side of the square, opposite the Casa Ducal, is the consistory of the village , the town hall. Although it is not known for sure, it is said that the building where it is located was owned by the Holy Inquisition. It has three floors, and the arcades on which it stands are formed by granite columns with basins on high plinths and 18th century Tuscan capitals with a medallion on the shaft of the central column with an inscription dated 1774.');
INSERT INTO monumento (categoriaMon, nombreMon, idioma, descMon) VALUES ('plaza', 'ayuntamiento', 'en', 'On the ground floor was the old prison, nowadays converted into a tourist office. The grille that covers the door and a tile placed on the lintel of the door with the inscription "Cárcel Pública" (Public Prison) remain from those times. The two upper floors have iron balconies on the first floor and wooden balconies on the second floor, with wooden railings on both. On the façade of the first floor balcony, there is a stone plaque commemorating the trip of King Alfonso XIII to La Alberca in 1922.');
INSERT INTO monumento (categoriaMon, nombreMon, idioma, descMon) VALUES ('plaza', 'teatro-cat1', 'en', 'The building on one of the corners of the square is perhaps one of the most remarkable buildings in the area. Formerly, and for many years, it was the Ducal house where the servant-administrator of the revenues of the Duchy of Alba in that area resided. Years later, the current theatre of La Alberca served as the barracks of the Civil Guard, as an old shop of butcher and as a stable. Today it is used for theatrical performances, informative talks, book presentations, children and folklore festivals and even as a cinema.');
INSERT INTO monumento (categoriaMon, nombreMon, idioma, descMon) VALUES ('plaza', 'teatro-cat1', 'en', 'Perhaps the most remarkable feature of the theatre of La Alberca are the columns, twelve in total. They are distributed as follows: Five facing the Plaza, forming arcades or porticoes; two embedded in each corner of the façade of the theatre and five in the side wall, which faces the street, also embedded in the wall. Almost all of them have a base and shaft, which in some is a hexagonal prism, in others octagonal, and in others cylindrical, longitudinal in the shaft, formed from the same stone as the column.');
INSERT INTO monumento (categoriaMon, nombreMon, idioma, descMon) VALUES ('plaza', 'teatro-cat1', 'en', 'The first one that forms part of the portico, next to the towers, has a relief on its capital that represents a head with an enormous mouth and seems to signify gluttony. The next one is probably the most curious. Its capital, like all the others, is quadrangular, and in the angle that faces inwards, it has an extremely realistic figure, with a full body, before another one behind it. It is the representation of sensuality.');
INSERT INTO monumento (categoriaMon, nombreMon, idioma, descMon) VALUES ('plaza', 'teatro-cat1', 'en', 'On the same capital, at the diagonal end, there is a head with large, oversized ears and an enormous mouth, with an expression of sarcastic laughter. It looks like a satyr, reminiscent of an ass. It could express laziness. On the other diagonal, at the end facing the Plaza, there is a head with a huge tongue, outside the mouth, emulating murmuring, and at the inner end of the same diagonal there is a head with a turban and a curly beard, a mixture of Moorish and Assyrian.');
INSERT INTO monumento (categoriaMon, nombreMon, idioma, descMon) VALUES ('plaza', 'teatro-cat2', 'en', 'The next two columns have four pomegranates each in their capitals. The one that forms the corner has the effigy of Jesus in the inner corner and, because of its long hair and elongated features, is in the Romanesque style. On the outside is a cross, but instead of being convex it is concave.');
INSERT INTO monumento (categoriaMon, nombreMon, idioma, descMon) VALUES ('plaza', 'teatro-cat2', 'en', 'The remaining seven crosses are all embedded in the wall. The two that form the corner of the façade are unremarkable. The third one, half a metre above the ground, has two heads in relief, perhaps representing animals, protruding from the shaft, very worn by time, and on the upper part, two pomegranates. The next one has another head on the capital with its tongue sticking out.');
