INSERT INTO monumento (categoriaMon, nombreMon, idioma, descMon) VALUES ('iglesia', 'iglesia-cat1', 'en', 'The present church of La Alberca is the great, magnificent and beautiful heart of the village. Built in a sober, granite style, the parish church dates from the first half of the 18th century. Specifically, construction of the church was begun on 9 May 1730 by the architect Manuel de Larra Churriguera, nephew of the well-known Churriguera family, famous for their contribution to the Spanish baroque.');
INSERT INTO monumento (categoriaMon, nombreMon, idioma, descMon) VALUES ('iglesia', 'iglesia-cat1', 'en', 'There is not much information about the old church. It is known that the need to build a new church was motivated by the fact that the previous one was in ruins, was made of wood and lacked foundations to hold it up. However, the present church still has the floor of the old church, which was in good condition, and underneath it were the graves of the faithful who maintained the church. Years later, these remains were exhumed and moved to the village cemetery. Only the remains of the costar of the chapel of the Virgen de los Dolores, whose tomb is in the chapel itself, were preserved.');
INSERT INTO monumento (categoriaMon, nombreMon, idioma, descMon) VALUES ('iglesia', 'iglesia-cat1', 'en', 'It is said that coins of all hierarchies were kept in the first stone that was laid, marked with two crosses in one of the corners of the church. Once the first stone was laid, the commissioners of the work decided that in order to achieve greater firmness, three courses of ashlar stone should be laid: two below, to prevent the water from flooding the foundations, and one above, to make the work more beautiful.');
INSERT INTO monumento (categoriaMon, nombreMon, idioma, descMon) VALUES ('iglesia', 'iglesia-cat1', 'en', 'It was this initiative that led to all the walls being built in ashlar. Once the first foundations of the new church were built, and due to the scarcity of funds to build it, some neighbours, and the town as a whole, were encouraged to pay for a row of ashlars, thus helping to complete the church.');
INSERT INTO monumento (categoriaMon, nombreMon, idioma, descMon) VALUES ('iglesia', 'iglesia-cat2', 'en', 'The construction of the church was completed on 4 August 1731 and to celebrate the completion of the work it was decided to hold three days of festivities in the village, with three sermons, two comedies and two bullfights, although the celebration was finally extended by four days, from 18 October to 21 October 1731.');
INSERT INTO monumento (categoriaMon, nombreMon, idioma, descMon) VALUES ('iglesia', 'iglesia-cat2', 'en', 'Years later, chapels were added to the original church, such as the Chapel of the Virgen del Rosario in 1777, the Chapel of the Virgen de los Dolores in 1875 or the presbytery of the main altar in 1832. The most curious thing about these extensions is the perfection with which they were attached to the rest of the church, giving the impression that they were not added after the main work.');
INSERT INTO monumento (categoriaMon, nombreMon, idioma, descMon) VALUES ('iglesia', 'iglesia-cat2', 'en', 'After the enlargements, the church, with a Latin cross plan measuring 40 metres long by 20 metres wide, reaching 31 metres at the transept, was distributed into three naves of three sections plus transept, separated by square pillars and semicircular arches.');
INSERT INTO monumento (categoriaMon, nombreMon, idioma, descMon) VALUES ('iglesia', 'iglesia-cat2', 'en', 'Unfortunately, the years take their toll and the church of La Alberca was not going to be any different. The foundations built in the 18th century have been suffering from different weather conditions that have caused "scars". A clear example is a small "gap" that can be seen in the upper part of the wall of the church located in the Solano Cimero, just above the marrano de San Antón, opened due to the earthquake suffered in Lisbon in 1755. In spite of everything, the church of La Alberca is nowadays a regular meeting place for the inhabitants and visitors of the village, and it still conserves the beauty and solemnity with which it was built.');
