INSERT INTO gastronomia (catGastro, idioma, descrGastro)  VALUES ('inicio','en','It can be said that the gastronomy of the Sierra de Francia, and therefore of La Alberca, is based on meats and cold meats, cured in the Serrano air, as well as on the very famous patatas meneás or the cabrito cuchifrito, without forgetting its incomparable nougat or its delicious sugared almonds.');
INSERT INTO gastronomia (catGastro, idioma, descrGastro)  VALUES ('inicio','en','Likewise, the hornazos, a pie made with cold meats, or the limón serrano, made with lemon, orange, hard-boiled egg and chorizo, are also very popular. Its wines, local vintages and sweets of extraordinary quality made with natural products, wafers, perrunillas, honey and pollen are also very important in the gastronomy of this charming village.');
INSERT INTO gastronomia (catGastro, idioma, descrGastro)  VALUES ('turroneras', 'en', 'For more than two centuries the turroneras albercanas have been producing their famous turrón using the same techniques and recipes as their ancestors. It is made simply: honey from the Sierra de Francia, almonds from Arribes del Duero, egg white and sugar. Its size is remarkable, as it is sold in pieces of two or three kilos that come out of large moulds weighing around 12 kg.');
INSERT INTO gastronomia (catGastro, idioma, descrGastro)  VALUES ('turroneras', 'en', 'Although almond nougat is the star product, several varieties are also available: soft, ground almonds, hazelnuts, etc. This product has its roots in the Arab repopulations of the mountains of Salamanca, who, faced with a surplus of honey, used it to produce nougat.');
INSERT INTO gastronomia (catGastro, idioma, descrGastro)  VALUES ('turroneras', 'en', 'The nougat of La Alberca has always been in the hands of women, who have passed on its production from generation to generation. This article is sold in shops and different stalls in the main square of La Alberca, and when Christmas comes, it is also sold in the arcades of the main square of Salamanca, which has become a tradition.');
INSERT INTO gastronomia (catGastro, idioma, nombreReceta, descrGastro, ingrReceta, pasosReceta) VALUES ('receta', 'en', 'serranolemon', 'Limón serrano is a surprising dish, as, despite being a cold dish, it turns out to be a winter recipe. It is believed to be of Jewish origin, which fits in perfectly with the historical past of the Sierra de Francia, although nowadays its consumption is linked to Christian festivities. In La Alberca it was traditionally eaten for breakfast on Holy Thursdays, although it is also traditionally eaten during carnival celebrations.', '4 oranges,2 lemons,4 eggs,1 clove of garlic,Paprika,4 choricillos,Red wine,Olive oil', '1.Peel the oranges and lemons, remove the white skins and cut them into pieces.--2.Peel and crush the garlic and add it to the orange and lemon pieces.--3. Add a good splash of red wine to taste to the previous mixture.--4. Cut the choricillos into slices and fry them in a frying pan with a little olive oil. Once lightly browned, add them to the rest of the ingredients.--5. Add more oil to the pan and fry the eggs. Once fried, add them on top of the warm salad. Add salt to taste and serve.--');
INSERT INTO gastronomia (catGastro, idioma, nombreReceta, descrGastro, ingrReceta, pasosReceta) VALUES ('receta', 'en', 'cuchifritokid', 'If there is one way to enjoy a good suckling kid, it is to make it cuchifrito. This is a very typical recipe from the Sierra de Francia and the province of Salamanca. It is also a very simple recipe that does not require a great deal of culinary knowledge and does not take too long to prepare, which makes it the ideal recipe for beginner cooks and lovers of mountain gastronomy.', '1 kg kid,4 cloves of garlic,2 bay leaves,2 glasses of white wine,Sweet paprika,Thyme,1 boiled egg,Potatoes,Olive oil,Salt.', '1. Cut the kid into small pieces and season to taste with salt, olive oil, a spoonful of sweet paprika, thyme and a glass of white wine. Leave to macerate for 2 hours.--2. In a frying pan with plenty of oil, add the chopped garlic, bay leaves, a little paprika and thyme. When the oil is hot, add the pieces of kid and fry until golden brown.--3. Once the pieces of kid are golden brown, add a small glass of white wine to the pan, increase the heat and leave to reduce for 10 minutes, covering the pan.--4. Once the 10 minutes have elapsed, remove the kid from the pan and serve with slices of boiled or fried potatoes (to taste) and hard-boiled egg.--');
INSERT INTO gastronomia (catGastro, idioma, nombreReceta, descrGastro, ingrReceta, pasosReceta) VALUES ('receta', 'en', 'zorongollo', 'Few words sound as traditional as "zorongollo". This is a very special salad of roasted peppers because, unlike other salads, this one does not have to be eaten freshly made, but must be left to rest so that the onion, the main ingredient of the dish, softens, softens its flavour and takes on the colour of the juice of the roasted peppers. It is a dish that is eaten especially in summer, and is a good accompaniment to grilled meat and fish.', '¾ red peppers,½ dried onion,2 ripe tomatoes,1 clove of garlic,Olive oil,Salt,Wine vinegar', '1. Wash the red peppers and tomatoes thoroughly, brush them with olive oil, wrap the tomatoes in aluminium foil and place everything on a baking tray.--2. Next, roast both the peppers and the tomatoes. To do this, preheat the oven to 200ºC. Once hot, place the tray prepared in the previous step at medium height for 45-50 minutes.--TIP: After 25-30 minutes, turn the peppers over.--3. When the tray is removed, transfer the peppers and tomatoes to a serving dish and cover them well so that they can "sweat" for approximately 30 minutes, in order to remove the skin easily. Reserve the juice from the roasted peppers.--4. Once the 30 minutes have elapsed, remove the skin and seeds and dice the tomatoes and cut the peppers into strips.--5. Peel the onion and garlic and chop them. Mix all the ingredients together and dress with olive oil, wine vinegar, salt and some of the juice from the roasted peppers. Leave the salad to rest for 18-24 hours in the refrigerator and serve.--');
INSERT INTO gastronomia (catGastro, idioma, nombreReceta, descrGastro, ingrReceta, pasosReceta) VALUES ('receta', 'en', 'turuletes', 'Turuletes, together with floretas, are another of the most typical sweets of La Alberca. Traditionally, these sweets were made at home when the holidays approached. They are an easy-to-make sweet that is very common at dawn in La Alberca, offered by the families of the bride and groom to the guests who came to sing to them and to curious onlookers who came to enjoy the event.', 'Water,Wheat flour,Salt,Frying oil,Sunflower oil,Sugar for breading', '1. Heat approximately one glass of sunflower oil in a casserole until it starts to boil. At the same time, heat a glass of water, without boiling, and once the water and oil are warm, pour everything into the bowl in which we will make the dough.--2. Add a pinch of salt and the sifted flour, and stir until the dough is uniform and free of lumps.--3. Take a small ball of dough and stretch it into a churro shape. Once it is in this shape, flatten it slightly and make a fold in the middle, fixing the fold with a fork.--4. Once the turulete has been shaped, heat oil in a pan and fry the turuletes until golden brown. When they are golden brown, remove them on absorbent paper and coat them in sugar. Serve.--');
INSERT INTO gastronomia (catGastro, idioma, nombreReceta, descrGastro, ingrReceta, pasosReceta) VALUES ('receta', 'en', 'waggishpotatoes', 'This is the funny name of this dish whose main ingredient is potatoes, and although it has spread throughout much of Spain, patatas meneás is a little gem of the gastronomy of Salamanca. These potatoes are a very simple dish, both in terms of ingredients and preparation, and can be served as an excellent tapa or even as a garnish for meat or fish, replacing the classic homemade mashed potato and giving it a special touch with paprika. The crispy and particularly tasty counterpoint is provided by the fried bacon, which traditionally crowns this delicious dish.', '400gr of potatoes,120gr of bacon,Salt,1 bay leaf,4 cloves of garlic,Olive oil,De la Vera Paprika', '1. Peel the potatoes, wash them and cut them into pieces. Boil them in water with a spoonful of salt and the bay leaf for approximately 20 minutes. Reserve a glass of the cooking water.--2. Cut the bacon into thick strips or cubes and fry until golden brown and crispy. Set aside.--3. Cut the garlic into slices and fry in the same oil as the bacon until lightly browned. Remove from the heat, add the paprika to the garlic and mix.--4. Return the garlic and paprika to the heat and pour in half a glass of the potato cooking liquid. Stir and bring to the boil for just one minute. Set aside.--5. Mash the cooked potatoes and add them to the sauce to "stir" all the ingredients in the same frying pan. Serve the potatoes piping hot with the bacon torreznos on top.');
INSERT INTO gastronomia (catGastro, idioma, nombreReceta, descrGastro, ingrReceta, pasosReceta) VALUES ('receta', 'en', 'hornazo', 'Hornazo is one of the most famous and representative products of the gastronomy of Salamanca. There are several varieties, but its preparation is quite similar. It is a pie made with a simple homemade dough filled with local products: pork fillets and good sausage.  Although it is a product that can be eaten all year round, it is a tradition in La Alberca to eat it on Easter Monday, on the day of the "Pendón".', '300gr flour,30gr lard,60ml water,10ml olive oil,2 eggs,1 salt teaspoon,200gr chorizo,300gr pork loin, 40ml white wine,25gr fresh yeast,½ paprika teaspoon', '1. Place the flour in a large bowl, make a hole in the middle and add the egg, oil, salt and paprika.--2. Heat the wine with the water and add the yeast and lard. Mix everything well and add to the large bowl. Knead everything well until you get a homogeneous dough.--3. Transfer the dough to another bowl, cover it with a damp cloth and leave it to rise for about 30 minutes.--4. After 30 minutes, sprinkle a flat surface with flour, divide the dough into two parts and roll them out with a rolling pin, giving them a rounded shape. Place 1 part on the baking tray and set the other part aside.--5. Place the pork loin and the chorizo sausage on the dough on the tray, and place the other part of the dough on top. Cut off the leftovers and join the two doughs well. Knead the leftovers and place them as decoration on top of the hornazo dough.--6. Beat the remaining egg and paint the hornazo dough. Once painted, bake in the oven at 200ºC for approximately 30 minutes, until golden brown. Leave to cool and serve.--');
INSERT INTO gastronomia (catGastro, idioma, nombreReceta, descrGastro, ingrReceta, pasosReceta) VALUES ('receta', 'en', 'perrunillas', 'Perrunillas are biscuits or pastries typical of the Sierra de Francia and Extremadura, very easy to make, with few ingredients and with all the flavour of tradition. Depending on the region, the recipe for making homemade perrunillas varies, but they all have in common the simplicity of their preparation and the ability to evoke aromas and flavours of yesteryear. It is also very typical to add a dash of aniseed. Because tasty and simple do not have to be at odds.', '125g sweet aniseed,1 sachet baking powder,150g sugar,1 egg white,125g lard,½ lemon zest,4 eggs,500g flour', '1. Put the butter in a bowl, add the aniseed and mix a little. Add the sugar, 2 egg yolks, 2 whole eggs and the lemon zest to the mixture. Whisk again.--2. Add the flour mixed with the yeast and mix until the dough is smooth and manageable. Add more flour if necessary.--3. Mix the egg whites until stiff and set aside.--4. Take portions of dough and make a kind of croquette. Flatten slightly and press with a finger to make an imprint.--5. Beat another egg white without stiffening it and brush the perrunillas with it.--6. On the marked mark, add a bow with the reserved egg white. Carefully roll the perrunillas in sugar on the side of the bun without letting the perrunilla out of your hands.--7. Preheat the oven to 250ºC. Once hot, bake the perrunillas for approximately 20 minutes or until golden brown.--');
INSERT INTO gastronomia (catGastro, idioma, nombreReceta, descrGastro, ingrReceta, pasosReceta) VALUES ('receta', 'en', 'maimonbun', 'The "bollo maimón", also called "Rosco de Bodas", is a typical sponge cake from the capital and the province of Salamanca. It dates back to the time when the Arabs lived in Spain alongside Jews and Christians. This sponge cake was a common wedding gift, and specifically in La Alberca, according to the protocol of Serrano love, the "maimona" sponge cake was one of the gifts that the groom had to give to the family of the bride at certain times of the year.  There are also references to the fact that the sponge cake or bollo maimón was also used to settle disputes and coexistence between different religions.', '100g sugar,4 eggs,Icing sugar,Butter,Brandy,150g flour (starch),1 lemon zest', '1. Add the eggs, sugar, one tablespoon of brandy and lemon zest to a bowl. Mix with a whisk until the mixture is frothy and white.--2. In the same bowl, gradually add the sifted flour and mix until it is completely incorporated.--3. Grease a cake mould with a hole in the centre with butter and pour the mixture into the mould.--4. Preheat the oven to 180ºC. Once hot, place the mould in the oven and bake the cake for about 25 minutes, until the cake is golden brown.--5. Once cooked, remove the sponge cake from the oven and cover it with icing sugar. Leave the cake to cool, remove from the mould and serve.--');
INSERT INTO gastronomia (catGastro, idioma, nombreReceta, descrGastro, ingrReceta, pasosReceta) VALUES ('receta', 'en', 'florets', 'Florets or floretas are another of most delicious typical sweets in Salamanca and they are easier to make than you might think. Traditionally, these sweets were typical of Carnival, Lent and Easter, but nowadays they can be found in bakeries at any time of the year. The mould used to make them, the "florero", is a tool that used to be passed down from mother to daughter along with the recipe.', '250ml milk,2 tablespoons sugar,1 egg,½ orange zest,30ml aniseed,200gr wheat flour,1 pinch of salt,Oil for frying,Cinnamon,Sugar for breading', '1. Start by beating the eggs and sugar in a bowl. When they are well mixed, add the milk, aniseed and orange zest.--2. Gradually add the flour and stir until it has a smooth, lump-free consistency. Strain the dough through a sieve if necessary. Transfer the dough to another bowl and leave to rest, covered, for about 20 minutes.--3. Heat plenty of oil in a deep frying pan over medium heat. Put the flower moulds into the oil so that they heat up at the same time. This step is very important so that the dough can adhere well to the mould.--4. When the oil is hot, uncover the batter and stir it a little until it has a light consistency. We introduce the mould into the batter up to the middle of the drawing without covering the whole flower and we put it immediately into the frying pan, taking care that it does not touch the bottom, and we shake it gently until the flower comes off.--5. Fry the flower until golden brown on both sides for a few seconds and transfer to absorbent paper before coating them generously in a mixture of cinnamon and sugar.--6. Reheat the mould and dip it in the batter again, repeating the previous operation until all the batter has been coated.--7. Dredge the portions in sugar and cinnamon. Serve the florets.--');
