INSERT INTO otroslugares (categoriaOtros, idioma, nombreOtro, descrOtro) VALUES ('peñadefrancia','en','convento','The convent of La Peña housed, during the months of May-November, a large community of Dominicans who moved to the convent of La Casa Baja, to the south of El Maíllo, during the winter season. La Peña was an autonomous convent from its foundation until 1835. In that year, due to the confiscation of Mendizábal, the monks were forced to abandon it. When the monks returned to the Sanctuary in 1900, it began to depend on the convent of San Esteban de Salamanca.');
INSERT INTO otroslugares (categoriaOtros, idioma, nombreOtro, descrOtro) VALUES ('peñadefrancia','en','elrollo','In the centre of the Plaza de la Peña de Francia is El Rollo, a symbol of the exemption from jurisdiction that the sanctuary enjoyed from 13th January 1445. In that year, eleven years after the discovery of the image of the Virgin of La Peña de Francia, King John II, seeing that the sanctuary of La Peña was becoming increasingly important and that this was giving rise to disputes over its possession between the towns of Granadilla and Miranda del Castañar, granted the prior of La Peña exemption from jurisdiction.');
INSERT INTO otroslugares (categoriaOtros, idioma, nombreOtro, descrOtro) VALUES ('peñadefrancia','en','elrollo','However, the claims of these towns to La Peña did not disappear with the royal decree, but continued for more than 70 years until, on 15 August 1521, Charles V, King of Spain at the time, endorsed the privilege of exemption and allowed the scroll to be placed in the sanctuary square, symbolising the exemption of jurisdiction.');
INSERT INTO otroslugares (categoriaOtros, idioma, nombreOtro, descrOtro) VALUES ('peñadefrancia','en','elrollo','The town of Miranda again tried to violently appropriate the sanctuary, so the emperor again ruled in favour of the Lord of La Peña. In spite of everything, the lawsuit dragged on for the rest of the 16th century. The kings and the courts always ruled in favour of the sanctuary, which maintained its privileges until the early years of the 19th century.');
