INSERT INTO tradiciones (nombreTrad, idioma, descr) VALUES ('lamozadeánimas','en', 'After reciting the second prayer, three more tolls are given and the procession continues through the village, without ceasing to pray. In addition to the daily shearing, there is a monthly one that is played on the first Friday of the month, which goes through the streets of the village in strict silence and is played only once.');
INSERT INTO tradiciones (nombreTrad, idioma, descr) VALUES ('elmarranodesanantón','en', 'The Marrano de San Antón is a tradition that amazes those who know it for the first time. It is a special celebration where a pig, also known as a garrapato or marrano, is released and walks freely through the streets of La Alberca, after being blessed, from the 13th of June until the 17th of January, when it is raffled among the inhabitants and visitors of the town.');
INSERT INTO tradiciones (nombreTrad, idioma, descr) VALUES ('elmarranodesanantón','en', 'This tradition has its origins in the late Middle Ages, when Christianised Arabs lived in La Alberca and raised the suspicions of the Inquisition. During the 16th century, the Jews used the pig as bait, fattening it for a few months and then slaughtering it to collect the product and donate it to the parish. It was a way of making known their religious stance, which was oriented towards Christianity, so that they did not feel threatened by the Holy Inquisition.');
INSERT INTO tradiciones (nombreTrad, idioma, descr) VALUES ('elmarranodesanantón','en', 'Over the years, the tradition has evolved, and nowadays, the pig, fattened by the neighbours during the time it is free, is auctioned, after the purchase of some ballots, and the proceeds are donated to social works or to an ONG.');
INSERT INTO tradiciones (nombreTrad, idioma, descr) VALUES ('elmarranodesanantón','en', 'This tradition has become so emblematic that the traditional pig now has a sculpture made of granite stone at the back of the church square, in the so-called Solano Cimero.');
INSERT INTO tradiciones (nombreTrad, idioma, descr) VALUES ('laloa','en', 'The Loa de la Asunción de Nuestra Señora, popularly known by the locals as La Loa, is a popular play that mixes religious and profane, rustic and allegorical elements, and which participates in what were medieval moralities, insofar as it invites the villagers to follow the path of good, avoiding falling into evil.');
INSERT INTO tradiciones (nombreTrad, idioma, descr) VALUES ('laloa','en', 'The actors and actresses of the Loa are the villagers themselves, who, voluntarily, and with the help of the cultural association Cateja Teatro, offer themselves every year to stage the performance. By dint of performing it year after year, they know the text of the Loa or parts of it by heart, which allows the villagers to play any role in the play without any problems and there is never a shortage of actors for the performance.');
INSERT INTO tradiciones (nombreTrad, idioma, descr) VALUES ('laloa','en', 'Originating in the 17th century, the Loa is an anonymous text in verse, in which we find innumerable features that relate it to the loas and entremeses of Spanish Baroque theatre, in which the archetypal struggle between evil and good, with the final triumph of the latter, is presented in the form of morality.  It may possibly have been composed by some educated local personage, and the text - of which there are four published texts - which has been passed from hand to hand for its learning and performance, has been shared and continuously retouched for each of the performances, always maintaining its unchanging structure.');
INSERT INTO tradiciones (nombreTrad, idioma, descr) VALUES ('laloa','en', 'Among the characters in the play, the most prominent and vigorous for creating greater dramatic or comic tension are those of the Devil and his court of deadly sins, and in contrast, the Angel, accompanied by the seven virtues represented by seven girls and the serpent, a wooden figure with the body and head of a goat, and with seven serpent heads representing the deadly sins. But the real driver of this dramatic spectacle is the character of the Gracioso, who, like the Galanes, belongs to the pastoral world and who, with his witty and comical speeches and witticisms, constantly provokes laughter in the audience.');
INSERT INTO tradiciones (nombreTrad, idioma, descr) VALUES ('laloa','en', 'Being one of the oldest autos sacramentales in Spain and having as the basis of its identity the very representation of the text itself, passed on from hand to hand, shared and continuously retouched by the actors themselves, but always maintaining its unchanging structure, has been enough for La Loa to be declared in 2021 as an Intangible Asset of Cultural Interest.');
INSERT INTO tradiciones (nombreTrad, idioma, descr) VALUES ('lasalboradas','en', 'The alborada is a nocturnal street singing. There are noisy and joyful alboradas, where the sounds blend in with the surrounding atmosphere.  In La Alberca there are two types:');
INSERT INTO tradiciones (nombreTrad, idioma, descr) VALUES ('lasalboradas','en', 'The religious alborada, sung on the occasion of the celebration of a religious feast, the night before it. The singers go around the village and stop at the houses of abbots, mayordomos, parish priests and municipal authorities, to all of whom they sing specific lyrics. The most famous alboradas are: the Alborada a la Virgen de la Asunción (14th August) or the Alborada de San Sebastián (19th January).');
INSERT INTO tradiciones (nombreTrad, idioma, descr) VALUES ('lasalboradas','en', 'The profane alborada, which is sung, above all, on the occasion of a wedding or marriage, the night before the celebration, when the guests sing it in front of the houses of the bride and the groom.');
INSERT INTO tradiciones (nombreTrad, idioma, descr) VALUES ('lasalboradas','en', 'The lyrics of the alboradas do not necessarily have to be the same each time they are sung, nor do they have to be sung in the same order. In the profane alboradas, the tradition is that the couplets are composed by friends or relatives according to the circumstances, to be sung and recited to the sound of castanets, tambourine music, the sounds of almireces, frying pans, bottles of aniseed and the continuous blast of rockets on the eve of the wedding.');
INSERT INTO tradiciones (nombreTrad, idioma, descr) VALUES ('lasalboradas','en', 'After singing, the girls appear with palmeros and trays full of turuletes, wafers, perrunillas or floretas, and it is the waiters who offer you a drink with jugs full of delicious homemade sangria. The bagpipes and drums are played again and the party begins, where the most daring people start dancing the "picaos" and "fandangos" with a lot of noise and endless joy.');
