INSERT INTO tradiciones (nombreTrad, idioma, descr) VALUES ('lasfuentesdelaalberca','en', 'Of the Pilarito fountain, formerly the round fountain and now disappeared, it is said that its water was always used after childbirth. The Cana or Canal fountain is said to have had special properties for making wax.');
INSERT INTO tradiciones (nombreTrad, idioma, descr) VALUES ('lasfuentesdelaalberca','en', 'The water from the Espeñitas spring was used to cure sick eyes. The Repesón fountain was the most used in summer due to the coldness of its water and the Fuente del Indiano, now in disuse, was said to be the most drinkable fountain and the most suitable for weak stomachs.');
INSERT INTO tradiciones (nombreTrad, idioma, descr) VALUES ('lasfuentesdelaalberca','en', 'Finally, the old fountain in the square, which disappeared in 1901, was known as "La fuente grande" (the big fountain). It was made of ashlar with eaves, and was considered to be a Romanesque monument built in the 12th century. It was the most used fountain by the inhabitants of the village.');
INSERT INTO tradiciones (nombreTrad, idioma, descr) VALUES ('lasfuentesdelaalberca','en', 'As a curiosity, it is said that in 1945, due to a great drought in the area, all the fountains of La Alberca stopped flowing except for two: the fountain of the Plaza and the fountain of La Balsá.');
INSERT INTO tradiciones (nombreTrad, idioma, descr) VALUES ('lasfuentesdelaalberca','en', 'Apart from the aforementioned fountains, we cannot forget many others that provide the village with pure and crystalline water: the Barrionuevo fountain, the Chorrito fountain, the Venaos fountain, located on the Camino de Las Raíces, or the Las Eras fountain, all of which are as important to La Alberca as any of the others, despite not possessing "curative abilities".');
INSERT INTO tradiciones (nombreTrad, idioma, descr) VALUES ('labodaalbercana-cat1','en', 'Weddings in La Alberca are still reminiscent of ancient celebrations, combining tradition and modernity. It is said to be one of the oldest weddings in Spain, where certain rituals and customs that have been handed down from generation to generation are followed and it is known for its authenticity and originality.');
INSERT INTO tradiciones (nombreTrad, idioma, descr) VALUES ('labodaalbercana-cat1','en', 'The night before the wedding, the so-called "Cena del Padrino" (The Supper of the Godfather) is held, where the two closest neighbours to the groom, accompanied by a drummer, offer the godfather a leg of lamb or kid and a jug of wine. After dinner, the best man will return the jug of wine to the groom, but with wine from his own house. After dinner, at midnight, the "alborada" is celebrated: first at the house of the groom house and then at the house of the bride, where sweets and sangria are handed out to all those who come to sing the "alborada".');
INSERT INTO tradiciones (nombreTrad, idioma, descr) VALUES ('labodaalbercana-cat1','en', 'On the wedding day, the bagpipes and drums, together with fireworks, announce the big day. Although nowadays there are hardly any occasions when it is possible to see the bride and groom in local costume, in the past the bride wore the traje de vistas, while the groom wore the traje serrano, with shoes, gaiters, headscarf and cape.  Nowadays it is more common for the most immediate family members to wear the local costumes.');
INSERT INTO tradiciones (nombreTrad, idioma, descr) VALUES ('labodaalbercana-cat1','en', 'Among the most outstanding characters at a wedding, without detracting from the bride and groom, are the "mozo del pollo" and the "moza de la pica". The mozo del pollo, carrying a bouquet of holly polished with ribbons, doughnuts and wafers and from which it is traditional to hang a chicken, rooster or rabbit that is offered to the parish priest at the end of the ceremony, goes to the house of the bride together with the male guests at the wedding to pick up the moza de la pica, the closest single female relative of the bride, and together they go to the house of the groom to pick him up and take him to the church. After picking up the groom, the retinue goes back to the house of the bride to go to the church.');
INSERT INTO tradiciones (nombreTrad, idioma, descr) VALUES ('labodaalbercana-cat1','en', 'After the religious ceremony, the chicken waiter throws the bouquet so that the village children can remove the decorations. Then, in the old days, the bride and her mother-in-law were accompanied in a pre-determined order to the "wedding house", or the house of the parents of the groom. There, after thanking everyone, the bride would go upstairs with her mother-in-law to a room, where they would have a secret conversation. Meanwhile, the groom would go with the godmother and the guests to her house, where they would have chocolate and biscuits, if they were "wedding guests", while the "accompanying guests" would stay outside, where the married brothers of the groom would serve them wine and biscuits. Today, all this has been replaced by the chocolate treat in one of the village hotels.');
INSERT INTO tradiciones (nombreTrad, idioma, descr) VALUES ('labodaalbercana-cat2','en', 'While all this was going on, the young wedding party would go to the new house of the bride and groom and break down the door and dismantle the whole house. The groom, alone, went to his parents house, being followed a little later by the rest of the cortege, who picked up the mother-in-law and left them alone for the first time, while they went to the house of the bride to look for the "Moza de la Pica", and they all went back to the wedding house, where the banquet would take place.');
INSERT INTO tradiciones (nombreTrad, idioma, descr) VALUES ('labodaalbercana-cat2','en', 'When the cortege had entered the house, a rocket was launched and the doors of the house were closed. Throughout the ceremony, the "Mozo del Pollo" would act as waiter, who would then eat the leftovers that had to be left for him. Afterwards, the spike was made, where the guests would deposit gifts and money on the bride and the table of the groom. After the spike, another rocket signalled the opening of the doors, with the drummer and the grooms coming out first. ');
INSERT INTO tradiciones (nombreTrad, idioma, descr) VALUES ('labodaalbercana-cat2','en', 'Little by little they all moved towards the place where the "cuartillas" were to take place, carried on the heads of the brides and grooms and placed within the measures of that capacity, while they tried not to flinch at the rockets thrown at their feet by the grooms. They are emptied before the bride and groom in white homemade linen bags, made for this event. After this act, the wedding waiters loaded the bags and the procession went to the new house of the couple, in the same order they had to follow when going to the church.');
INSERT INTO tradiciones (nombreTrad, idioma, descr) VALUES ('labodaalbercana-cat2','en', 'The door of the new home of the couple is opened by the "Moza de la pica", who gave way first to the bride, then to the groom, and then to the rest of the procession. Now it was time for the spouses to treat their companions to wine, cakes and flowers, until they said their goodbyes. Almost immediately it was time for the first dance, the dance in the square, which would be opened by the bride with the "Moza de la Pica" and the groom with the best man.');
INSERT INTO tradiciones (nombreTrad, idioma, descr) VALUES ('labodaalbercana-cat2','en', 'Then, the "wedding guests" would go to the "wedding house" for dinner, where in the evening, to conclude the wedding, another dance would take place, in which all the men had to dance with the bride and all the women with the groom, giving them the "dádiva" at the end, consisting of a small gift, usually money.');
