INSERT INTO fiesta (idioma, nombreFiesta, descrFiesta) VALUES ('en', 'sananton', 'The feast of San Antón (Saint Anthony, Abbot), which is celebrated on 17 January, is a feast to bless the livestock of the village, to protect them from plagues and diseases. The day before, in the afternoon, the feast is announced by a parade with the tambourine and bagpipes. On the feast day, a mass and procession with the image of the saint is held in the morning around the church.');
INSERT INTO fiesta (idioma, nombreFiesta, descrFiesta) VALUES ('en', 'sananton', 'The saint has stewards, who play a special role on this day. In the afternoon, the rosary is recited and the animals are blessed by the priest in front of the church. In the old days, the cattle were given three laps around the church and surrounding streets, a good complement to the blessing with holy water. However, perhaps the most striking aspect of this fiesta is the so-called Marrano San Antón, something that had been lost and which has been recovered in recent years.');
INSERT INTO fiesta (idioma, nombreFiesta, descrFiesta) VALUES ('en', 'sansebastian', 'The festivity of San Sebastián consists of a mass with a procession around the church, with the image of the saint. The most significant part of this celebration is the "alborada" or "alborá" which is sung to the saint in the streets of the village on the night of the eve, i.e. the night of 19 January, sung to the majordomos and authorities of the village, with each person having their own personalised verse.');
INSERT INTO fiesta (idioma, nombreFiesta, descrFiesta) VALUES ('en', 'sansebastian', 'There is great devotion to this saint in La Alberca, as the people, in their collective memory, credit him with having saved them from the plague of 1918, an event to which the "alborá" alludes. In addition, it is said that to belong to the brotherhood of the saint you have to be single.');
INSERT INTO fiesta (idioma, nombreFiesta, descrFiesta) VALUES ('en', 'lascandelas', 'Las Candelas is the feast of the purification of the Virgin, after the post-birth quarantine, and the presentation of the Child in the temple, which is celebrated on 2 February. This is one of the first times that the image of the Virgin of the Assumption is carried in procession, but it is the only time that it is carried with the Child.');
INSERT INTO fiesta (idioma, nombreFiesta, descrFiesta) VALUES ('en', 'lascandelas', 'The Virgin carries a large candle, from which three other candles emanate, representing the Child, herself and Saint Joseph, respectively. On her right arm she carries a large pike*, which is adorned with flowers. On the left is the Child, who in turn is holding a small pike around his neck.');
INSERT INTO fiesta (idioma, nombreFiesta, descrFiesta) VALUES ('en', 'lascandelas', 'Up to twenty-four charms also hang from the neck of the Child: coral dummy, Indian chestnut, articulated trout, crescent moon with ruby and nail, rattlesnake, milk stone, hoof of the great beast..., reliquaries and amulets, whose function is to help the Child to grow up well, not to be spoiled in his development, and also to prevent someone from harming him, that is, to cast the evil eye on him.');
INSERT INTO fiesta (idioma, nombreFiesta, descrFiesta) VALUES ('en', 'lascandelas', 'In La Alberca, the charms also hang from the bracelets of the Vistas costume. Superstitious elements are thus added to a religious figure, such as the Child, by placing the charms around his neck, elements in which the women of La Alberca would undoubtedly believe; and it is not difficult to imagine how, when the child was born, his mother, in order to prevent him from getting the evil eye, hung the mandatory charms around his neck, which have continued to be preserved as they have become jewellery in the costume of "Vistas".');
INSERT INTO fiesta (idioma, nombreFiesta, descrFiesta) VALUES ('en', 'lascandelas', 'Las Candelas is, as we have said, the feast of the purification of the Virgin after childbirth and quarantine, and the presentation of the Child in the temple. The whole village accompanies them with the pikes in this celebration, and the women carry a candle each in the procession, which, once blessed, they will keep in their homes to light it on stormy days in front of the images or religious images in their rooms, and thus prevent any misfortune from occurring.');
INSERT INTO fiesta (idioma, nombreFiesta, descrFiesta) VALUES ('en', 'lascandelas', 'The pikes are blessed in the church, during the celebration of mass, and once blessed, the whole village will taste this bread, symbol of purification: one is given to the parish priest; another to the sacristan, the altar servers and the waitresses of the Virgin . The sick, the schoolchildren, who will take them to their classes, and even the livestock will also taste them. ');
INSERT INTO fiesta (idioma, nombreFiesta, descrFiesta) VALUES ('en', 'lascandelas', 'Each neighbour, for his part, also brings his own pikes to the mass, where they are blessed and then distributed among the members and livestock of the family, since it is said that each person or animal, on tasting them, is purified. And just as the Virgin and Child carry their pikes, there is also the custom of putting them on other images in the church, both of virgins and saints.');
INSERT INTO fiesta (idioma, nombreFiesta, descrFiesta) VALUES ('en', 'lascandelas', 'There is another rite, derived from this one of Las Candelas: women, after giving birth and forty days have passed since the birth, present themselves with their child in the church, like the Virgin and Child, with a candle and a loaf of bread. The woman who accompanies the new-born child takes holy water from the church door, since it is assumed that the woman has the stain of pregnancy and childbirth, and thus begins the purification, in the image and likeness of the Virgin.');
INSERT INTO fiesta (idioma, nombreFiesta, descrFiesta) VALUES ('en', 'carnavales', 'Not to miss the traditional carnival figures in La Alberca is one of the reasons for this special celebration. Among them is the pataheno, who does not go unnoticed by those who come to enjoy our festivities. He is a man dressed in sacks filled with hay and straw, who is part of a burlesque representation of a bullfight. His attire makes him move clumsily and he often falls to the ground as he tries to avoid the "bull".');
INSERT INTO fiesta (idioma, nombreFiesta, descrFiesta) VALUES ('en', 'carnavales', 'The other main figure in the bullfights, the bull or heifer, is symbolised by the mozotoros. Instead of horns, they carry pitchforks or sticks to swing the straw and are usually dressed in dark colours, carrying cowbells and different branches. Their mission is to ram the patahenos to knock them to the ground. It is all part of a kind of theatrical performance that has been going on for many years and which makes the existing public part of the festivity.');
INSERT INTO fiesta (idioma, nombreFiesta, descrFiesta) VALUES ('en', 'carnavales', 'On the other hand, there are the maragatas, women dressed in manila shawls and sayas, who cover their faces with a handkerchief, held tightly in place with a hat. In the past, they used to enter the square on horseback, accompanied by horsemen dressed in the costumes of the Serranos. The Maragatos also take part in the fiesta. The children await their arrival, always accompanied by sweets.');
INSERT INTO fiesta (idioma, nombreFiesta, descrFiesta) VALUES ('en', 'carnavales', 'Finally, the ensabanados, dressed in sheets, carry a stick to prevent people from approaching the maragatas.');
